review:
The Hula Dancer is one of the latest collectible minifigures from LEGO.&nbsp; She will make a great addition to your collection.&nbsp; At first I found myself on the fence about 
buying her, but after I had her in hand I started to see the 
possibilities of the figure as well as the parts.<br><h4>Design</h4>The legs of the figure appear to have on a green bathing suit.&nbsp; The torso of the figure has printing that looks like a green bikini top with a flower lei.&nbsp; The face has a wonderful smile, and the hair is black with a printed flower!&nbsp; She comes with the LEGO version of a grass skirt (made of similar material to minifig capes), and two of the maraca piece from the Series 2 Mariachi, which in this case I assume are meant to represent gourd rattles such as Uli uli.<br><h4>Playability</h4>The figure as a whole would fit equally well in many LEGO themes.&nbsp; For LEGO City she could be at a vacation paradise (need somewhere for the planes to fly, right?) or dressed up for a beach party.&nbsp; If Pirates is your thing, she could be a native islander.&nbsp; I could see her in Indiana Jones and other adventure themes as well.<br><h4>Parts</h4>If you want to use the parts rather than the figure, again you have several possibilities.&nbsp; The hairpiece with the printed flower could be used for a flower child of the 60's or a minifig out on a romantic date.&nbsp; The legs could be used on a male figure to represent a green bathing suit.&nbsp; I haven't thought of alternate uses for the gourd rattles (other than Maracas) or grass skirt yet, but I'm sure there are plenty.<br><h4>Cons</h4>There is one thing LEGO could have done better, making the lei a separate piece instead of printing it on the torso.&nbsp; That would have opened the possibility of having other tourist figures wearing a lei, and it also would have allowed you to use the green bikini torso as a more general female bathing suit.<br><h4>Summary</h4>Overall I really like the hair printing, and the add-on skirt is great as well.&nbsp; Hopefully we'll see more cloth skirts instead of dresses printed on slope pieces.&nbsp; This is a great minifigure and hopefully a sign of more good things to come.&nbsp;
